Ukraine on its way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and they will never find common ground," said Rudyard Kipling once.
Ukraine lies undoubtedly in the East, but in Eastern Europe.
As the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the predominant goal for many of us.
The road there was however not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on 31 March has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to continue on this path.
I am a Social Democrat and was never a member of the Communist Party, although I was indeed successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It is beyond dispute for me that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine faces in finding a connection to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country possessed an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural cultivation areas were practically crippled by outdated machinery parks and the lethargy of the state-run agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is massive.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We have botched the reform entirely on our own.
For often we wanted to import established concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy - in a weakened form, and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic undertones in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted citizens' rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been severed from European history for centuries was certainly painful, but has gained momentum, even though we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as more open, sentimental, friendly, and family-conscious, but also more chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
We are Europeans.
This can be seen on the streets and squares of Kiev.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich, while pedestrians in Moscow still have to protect themselves from reckless drivers.
In Kiev, there is now a thriving café scene and friendly public spaces where people can stop and enjoy life.
The young people are learning English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the internet in the Internet cafes.
But these are just the romantic digressions of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The detached view of a professional politician, which I am, sees more profound changes.
In the past decade, a development from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms driven by corrupt motives and ultimately to the gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
Initially, the reform of the state sparked hostile sentiment among both bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and ill-considered reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "template" reform: the state must shrink, people thought, and then the government would run smoothly.
Nobody thought that countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
The problem is not only one of size, but also of organization and purpose.
The realization that the government doesn't necessarily become better just because you cut red tape led us to the second stage of our reform process.
The state was gradually reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
They established new departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility.
This led to the stabilization of the work of the government ministries.
At the beginning, the authority assigned to these new areas was somewhat too broad to effectively organize their work.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may occasionally grumble about these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (if begrudgingly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only extreme radicals and populists - of whom there are still too many among us - can afford to take a detached attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not simple.
Why?
The Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial mentality cannot admit its own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
In the measure we shed our provincial impulse to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mockingly referred to as "the sick man of Europe".
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to acknowledge that their country inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
In the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even more ailing ourselves, but the recent elections, which stripped the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "mighty parties" under President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the periphery of politics.
The reform parties and European parties have triumphed.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the periphery of Europe, we want to establish a society where there are no outsiders or peripheral figures.
As the great American writer Vladimir Nabokov, who was already American at the time, said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous path to Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
